    <p>Imagine two film plots, A and B. In Film A, a ship runs into an iceberg. The ship sinks. The noble captain selflessly, heart-wrenchingly rescues all the passengers from drowning. Heâ€™s the last person to leave the ship and clamber into a lifeboatâ€”just moments before it disappears forever into a spout of foam. In Film B, the captain steers the ship around the iceberg, keeping a sensible distance. Which film would you pay to watch? A, of course. But which situation would you prefer as an actual passenger on the ship? Thatâ€™s equally obvious: B. Letâ€™s say the examples are real. What would happen next? Captain A would be invited onto talk shows. Heâ€™d get a six-figure book contract. Heâ€™d hang up his captainâ€™s hat and earn a living as a motivational speaker at client events and team meetings for major corporations. His home town would name a street after him and his children, for the first time ever, would feel something like pride in their father. Captain B, on the other hand, would keep avoiding obstacles until his retirement many years later, sticking to Charlie Mungerâ€™s maxim: â€œI have a rule in life, if there is a big whirlpool you donâ€™t want to miss it with 20 feetâ€”you round it with 500 feet.â€ Although B is demonstrably the better captain, A is the one we celebrate. Why? Because successes achieved through prevention (i.e., failures successfully dodged) are invisible to the outside world. The financial press loves nothing better than a turnaround manager, and thatâ€™s all well and good, but they should applaud managers who prevent companies needing a turnaround in the first place even louder. Yet because preventative successes arenâ€™t externally apparent, they fly under the mediaâ€™s radar. Only the individual manager and his or her team know how wisely they actedâ€”and even then to a limited degree. As a result, we systematically overemphasize the role of successful generals, politicians, emergency surgeons and therapists while underempha