  </li>
  <li>Focus, time and money are our three most important resources. The latter two are most familiar. Thereâ€™s even a science devoted to time and moneyâ€”referred to in that context as â€œworkâ€ and â€œcapital.â€ Focus, however, is little understood, although today itâ€™s the most valuable of these three resources, the most crucial to our success and our wellbeing. Unfortunately, when it comes to focus we tend to commit systematic errors. Here are several key ways you can avoid them.
    <ul>
      <li>One: donâ€™t confuse whatâ€™s new with whatâ€™s relevant. Every noveltyâ€”product, opinion, news itemâ€”wants an audience. The louder the world, the louder the novelty must shout in order to be heard. Donâ€™t take this noise too seriously. Most of whatâ€™s hailed as revolutionary is irrelevant.</li>
      <li>Two: avoid content or technology thatâ€™s â€œfree.â€ Theyâ€™re the definition of focus traps, because theyâ€™re financed by advertising. Why would you voluntarily walk into a trap?</li>
      <li>Three: give everything â€œmultimediaâ€ a wide berth. Images, moving images andâ€”in the futureâ€”virtual reality accelerate your emotions above a safe speed, markedly worsening the quality of your decision-making. Information is best absorbed in written form, from documents with the fewest possible hyperlinksâ€”books, ideally.</li>
      <li>Four: be aware that focus cannot be divided. Itâ€™s not like time and money. The attention youâ€™re giving your Facebook stream on your mobile phone is attention youâ€™re taking away from the person sitting opposite.</li>
      <li>Five: act from a position of strength, not weakness. When people bring things to your attention unasked, youâ€™re automatically in a position of weakness. Why should an advertiser, a journalist or a Facebook friend decide where you direct your focus? That Porsche advert, article about the latest Trump tweet or video clip of hilariously adorable puppies is probably not something thatâ€™s going to make you happy or move you forwards. Even without an Instagram account, the philosopher Epictetus came to a similar conclusion two thousand years ago: â€˜If a person gave your body to any stranger he met on his way, you would certainly be angry. And do you feel no shame in handing over your own mind to be confused and mystified by anyone who happens to verbally attack you?â€™</li>
