  <li>
    <p>Another aspect: focus and happiness. What does focus have to do with happiness? Everything. â€œYour happiness is determined by how you allocate your attention,â€ wrote Paul Dolan. The same life events (positive or negative) can influence your happiness strongly, weakly or not at allâ€”depending on how much attention you give them.
Essentially, you always live where your focus is directed, no matter where the atoms of your body are located. Each moment comes only once. If you deliberately focus your attention, youâ€™ll get more out of life. Be critical, strict and careful when it comes to your intake of informationâ€”no less critical, strict and careful than you are with your food or medication</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Avoid ideologies and dogmas at all costâ€”especially if youâ€™re sympathetic to them. Ideologies are guaranteed to be wrong. They narrow your worldview and prompt you to make appalling decisions. I donâ€™t know of a single dogmatist with anything approaching a good life. Many people donâ€™t notice that theyâ€™re falling for an ideology. How do you recognize one? Here are three red flags: a) they explain everything, b) theyâ€™re irrefutable, and c) theyâ€™re obscure. An excellent example of an irrefutable ideology with an explanation for everything is Marxism. If the concentration of wealth in a society increases, the faithful will immediately attribute it to the fundamental evil of capitalismâ€”as described by Marx. If inequality decreases, however, they will explain it as the development of history toward a classless societyâ€”as predicted by Marx. At first glance, such irrefutability appears to be an advantage. Who wouldnâ€™t want a theory on hand thatâ€™s so powerful it means youâ€™re always right? In reality, however, irrefutable theories are anything but invulnerableâ€”in fact, theyâ€™re very easily exposed. When you meet someone showing signs of a dogmatic infection, ask them this question: â€œTell me what specific facts youâ€™d need in order to give up your worldview.â€ If they donâ€™t have an answer, keep that person at armâ€™s length. You should ask yourself the same question, for that matter, if you suspect youâ€™ve strayed too far into dogma territory. To be as unassailable as possible, ideologies often hide behind a smokescreen of obscurantism. Thatâ€™s the third red flag by which to recognize an ideology. Hereâ€™s an example: the ordinarily clear and articulate theologian Hans KÃ¼ng describes God as â€œthe absolute-relative, here-hereafter, transcendent-immanent, all-embracing and all-permeating most real reality in the heart of things, in man, in the history of mankind, in the world.â€ All-explaining, irrefutable and utterly obscure!</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Think independently, donâ€™t be too faithful to the party line, and above all give dogmas a wide berth. The quicker you understand that you donâ€™t understand the world, the better youâ€™ll understand the world</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>The next time youâ€™re about to make an important decision, mull it over carefullyâ€”but only to the point of maximum deliberation. Youâ€™ll be surprised how quickly you reach it. Once youâ€™re there, flick off your torch and switch on your floodlight. Itâ€™s as useful in the workplace as it is in the home, whether youâ€™re investing in your career or in your love life</p>
